            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sarah Riley\u2019s story begins not in the fog-laced streets of San Francisco, but under the wide, quiet skies of suburban Wisconsin. Raised by a practical engineer father and a reserved mother, her childhood home was stable and loving, but emotionally muted. Sarah, a sensitive and observant child, found her voice not in conversation, but in sketchbooks and clay. Art was her first language, a way to process a world she felt more than she could articulate.\n\nHer educational journey began with a practical B.A. in Psychology, a nod to her family\u2019s pragmatism. However, a post-college volunteer position at a community arts center for at-risk youth changed her trajectory. Witnessing a withdrawn teenager finally open up while painting a mural was a profound turning point. It was then she discovered Expressive Arts Therapy, a field that could unite her innate artistic sensibility with her desire to heal. She moved to San Francisco for her graduate degree at the California Institute of Integral Studies, feeling an immediate kinship with the city\u2019s culture of acceptance and creativity.\n\nThe biggest shift in her adult life was her divorce at 38. Amicable but deeply sorrowful, the separation dismantled the life she thought she had built. Instead of crumbling, Sarah used the experience as a catalyst for independence. She left the agency where she worked and poured her savings and energy into opening her own private practice in a sunlit office in Hayes Valley.\n\nToday, Sarah\u2019s life is a testament to the integration she preaches. Her mornings start with yoga before she hops on her bicycle for the 2.8-mile commute, a daily ritual that connects her to the city\u2019s rhythm. Her days are spent guiding clients\u2014couples navigating conflict, individuals grappling with trauma\u2014using paint, poetry, and movement to unlock what words alone cannot reach. Her social life is a small, intimate circle of fellow therapists and artist friends. Her apartment in NOPA, filled with plants and her own abstract paintings, is a sanctuary. Looking ahead, Sarah dreams of writing a book to make therapeutic art accessible to a wider audience and perhaps leading retreats in Big Sur. She came to San Francisco to find a career, but ultimately, she built a life that was, in itself, a work of art."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers her first morning in the city, just after moving for grad school. Waking up in her tiny Richmond district apartment, she saw the fog wasn't a bleak covering but a soft, grey embrace, muting the world's harsh edges. Unlike the stark clarity of a Wisconsin winter, this felt gentle and mysterious. Instead of feeling lost, she felt held. That morning, she knew she hadn't just moved to a new city; she had come home to a place that understood the beauty in what isn't always sharp and defined.\n\n2.\nAt 38, after the divorce papers were signed, she and her ex-husband divided their shared art. Standing in their nearly empty living room, he handed her the small abstract painting they'd bought on their first anniversary. There was no argument, just a quiet, aching finality. In that moment of profound loss, she also felt a flicker of ownership. She realized her life, not just her walls, was now entirely hers to curate. It was the sorrowful, necessary act of clearing a canvas for what would come next.\n\n3.\nThe day she got the keys to her Hayes Valley office, she didn't bring in furniture. She just brought her yoga mat. After her first client session was officially booked, she sat alone on the floor as sunlight streamed through the large windows. The silence was both terrifying and exhilarating\u2014the weight of her new independence. That simple act of claiming the empty space wasn't about business; it was the first brushstroke in designing a life built on her own terms, one of healing and self-reliance.\n\n4.\nA few years into her private practice, a combat veteran she\u2019d worked with for months, who had barely spoken, finally picked up a piece of clay. Without a word, he molded a small, fragile bird with one broken wing. He placed it in her hand, his eyes filled with a grief he could not articulate. A wave of profound humility washed over Sarah. It wasn't a victory, but a sacred trust. The memory cemented her belief that her role wasn't to fix, but to simply create a safe space for the unspoken to be made visible.\n\n5.\nOn a random Tuesday in her early forties, she was biking home from her office. Spontaneously, she pedaled through Golden Gate Park all the way to Ocean Beach just as the sun was setting. Standing there, feeling the wind and the satisfying ache in her legs, a deep sense of peace settled over her. There was no great achievement or milestone, just the perfect, unforced contentment of being exactly where she was. This quiet moment, she realized, was the masterpiece she had been building all along."
